# THIS IS NOT A REAL KEY.
#
# The auth-service requires an RSA private key to sign JWT access/refresh tokens.
# Real keys must NEVER be committed. The .gitignore rules block
# apps/*/src/main/resources/keys/*.pem from being tracked.
#
# Local development setup
# -----------------------
# 1. Generate a 2048-bit RSA keypair (do this once per dev machine):
#
#      openssl genpkey -algorithm RSA \
#        -pkeyopt rsa_keygen_bits:2048 \
#        -pkeyopt rsa_keygen_pubexp:65537 \
#        -out apps/auth-service/src/main/resources/keys/private.pem
#
#      openssl rsa \
#        -in  apps/auth-service/src/main/resources/keys/private.pem \
#        -pubout \
#        -out apps/auth-service/src/main/resources/keys/public.pem
#
# 2. Copy the matching public.pem to the consuming services so signature
#    verification works locally:
#      apps/admin-service/src/main/resources/keys/public.pem
#      apps/community-service/src/main/resources/keys/public.pem
#
# 3. Run the auth-service with the `local` Spring profile, OR override the
#    path explicitly via env vars:
#
#      JWT_PRIVATE_KEY_PATH=file:/abs/path/to/private.pem
#      JWT_PUBLIC_KEY_PATH=file:/abs/path/to/public.pem
#
# Production / staging
# --------------------
# Keys must be supplied at runtime from a secret store (Vault, AWS Secrets
# Manager, K8s Secret) and `JWT_PRIVATE_KEY_PATH` / `JWT_PUBLIC_KEY_PATH`
# must point at filesystem paths — not classpath: resources.
#
# A startup guard (`JwtKeyPathValidator`) refuses to boot when a non-local
# profile is active and the configured path still resolves to a classpath
# resource.
